 **** UML DIAGRAM :     
   FOR STrategy Design Pattern 

Context
  - strategy: Strategy
  + setStrategy(s: Strategy)
  + executeStrategy()

Strategy (interface)
  + execute()

ConcreteStrategyA
  + execute()

ConcreteStrategyB
  + execute()



 *** Definition : 
    The Strategy Design Pattern is a behavioral design pattern that enables you to define a family of algorithms, encapsulate each one into a separate class, and make them interchangeable at runtime.
             or
   In Simple Terms:
      It allows you to select an algorithmâ€™s behavior at runtime by encapsulating different behaviors (strategies) in separate classes and letting a context class use them interchangeably.

*** ðŸ“¦ Example Context:
    ->  You have different payment methods (CreditCard, PayPal, UPI).
    -> Instead of hardcoding if-else blocks, we define each payment method as a strategy.
    -> The ShoppingCart class (context) delegates the pay() action to whatever strategy is set.

*** UML Diagram for shoppingCart example:
  
          +------------------------+
          |    <<interface>>       |
          |     PaymentStrategy    |
          +------------------------+
          |+ pay(amount: int): void|
          +------------------------+
                   â–²
                   |
   +-----------------------------+   +-----------------------------+
   |     CreditCardPayment       |   |       PayPalPayment         |
   +-----------------------------+   +-----------------------------+
   | + pay(amount: int): void    |   | + pay(amount: int): void    |
   +-----------------------------+   +-----------------------------+

                 â–²
                 |
          +------------------------------------------------+
          |          ShoppingCart                          |
          +------------------------------------------------+
          | - paymentStrategy: PaymentStrategy             |
          +------------------------------------------------+
          | + setPaymentStrategy(s: PaymentStrategy): void |
          | + checkout(amount: int): void                  |
          +------------------------------------------------+


*** CODE CONTROL FLOW :

 Main.main() 
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€> new ShoppingCart()
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€> cart.setPaymentStrategy(new CreditCardPayment())
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ ShoppingCart.paymentStrategy = CreditCardPayment
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€> cart.checkout(100)
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ CreditCardPayment.pay(100)
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€> cart.setPaymentStrategy(new PayPalPayment())
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ ShoppingCart.paymentStrategy = PayPalPayment
â”‚
â””â”€â”€> cart.checkout(200)
        â””â”€â”€ PayPalPayment.pay(200)

*** âœ… How It Works:

 -> ShoppingCart is the context class that uses a PaymentStrategy.

 -> PaymentStrategy is an interface with a pay() method.

 -> CreditCardPayment and PayPalPayment are two interchangeable strategies.

 -> The strategy can be set dynamically at runtime using setPaymentStrategy().

 -> checkout() delegates the payment logic to the current strategy.

